messages.text: I think Haven1 will be a big player in next bull market. EU, UK and even US are trying to speed up secure regulations for crypto space as they know that Crypto is not just a speculation but a next step in general global adoption. H1 technically will solve issues that were not solved yet, especially on DeFi. I am exited to see what future will bring. Personally I am glad that I am there with yield app almost since the beginning. I must say that it‚Äôs a pleasure to get help and clear answers from the support team. It‚Äôs a big plus that you don‚Äôt need to speak to bots to reach a real person on the opposite site. From past two weeks I tried to get some support from other brands (not related to crypto) and auto bots are almost everywhere, sometimes really hard and it‚Äôs time consuming to reach a solution.

text:
‚ÄûWhat will happen to YLD?
The development of Haven1 is exciting news for holders of the YLD token ‚Äì the membership token of the Yield App platform. All holders of YLD will become stakeholders in Haven1 through a 1:1 token swap. This will take place alongside the official launch of Haven1 in 2024. Full details will be announced later in 2023.
As such, the launch of Haven1 will be bootstrapped by up to 40,000 existing YLD token holders. The H1 token will also become the membership token of the Yield App platform. ‚Äû

All holders of YLD will become stakeholders in Haven1 through a 1:1 token swap. This will take place alongside the official launch of Haven1 in 2024. Full details will be announced later in 2023.
As such, the launch of Haven1 will be bootstrapped by up to 40,000 existing YLD token holders. The H1 token will also become the membership token of the Yield App platform. ‚Äû

messages.text:
I'm sure Nenad is sorting you out in DMs but I'd just like to clarify for others here.

We have a system for withdrawals. It's automated just like you'd expect from any other platform or exchange. The difference is, we have additional layers of security and when something is flagged we have staff on 24/7 to look at it and request more info where necessary. 

These staff are all in-house, seasoned veterans.

There's always a tug of war between security and convenience. Our track record shows that our approach works, even if it means that sometimes a client has to re-verify themselves.

messages.text:
That UK law isn't special, I am sure it's like that for majority of the countries.

The companies like blockfi aren't banks and therefore aren't protected by other stuff specifically to protect depositors like FDIC. That goes for yield app too.

I know a top manager of a crypto exchange already working in a crypto firm in another country because law is still catching up and police ain't bothered for transnational cases.

A ton of defi stuff is even worse, got rugged? No one gets punished at all. The only exception is when it gets as big as Terra Luna, that should say a lot about what is needed to be done. 

Way too much scammers, way too much rug, not nearly enough punishment and oversight.

Personally, everyone should always opt for bitcoin only, it's the closest to asset nor security, but alas everyone wanna get rich and the next trendy thing. 

At the end, a good market should have bare minimum of oversight and rules, which crypto is lacking.

Hey. As promised, coming back to you with answer (received with our Compliance team help so I will be partially quoting professionalist in that matter, excuse my limited ISO knowledge!):

‚ÄûISO20022 is not a crypto ISO, but a payment one (fiat). It‚Äôs not on our side to implement it but we will speak to our banking partners to verify their readiness and timelines for implementation. 
Furthermore, we are not a banking or payments institution. This means that even if our banking partners implement ISO20022, there may still be time delays for allocation of payments.‚Äù

We‚Äôve voluntarily withdrawn our Estonian license, effective 12am UTC, 27 May. Over the past year, we‚Äôve worked on securing new licenses in multiple jurisdictions - including another European country - ahead of the introduction of MiCA.

There will be no impact on the services provided by Yield App, nor do you need to take any action to continue using the platform. Our team is diligently working to finalize the new licenses in the coming weeks, and we‚Äôll keep you updated as this is completed.

messages.text: Why did you withdraw it

The regulatory landscape in Europe has changed significantly over the last 12 months, particularly in some of the smaller country jurisdictions ahead of the introduction of MiCA and the European wide harmonization of VASP licensing rules. In order to position the business for future growth and to ensure broad oversight of the different activities, including Digital Wealth, the change is preemptive to align our platform to the highest standards of operation.

We‚Äôve always approached regulation proactively. We already hold ourselves to a higher standard than any individual license.¬† What we have achieved already with fiat partnerships during a time when banks have been pulling back from crypto, is an example of this. 

As we continue to build and offer more services, forge more partnerships to expand our fiat facilities etc, having top tier licenses will serve to also strengthen these partnerships. 

There's also the fact that the majority of our clients are in Europe and I know from my own conversations with hundreds of potential and existing clients that having strong licenses helps build confidence in the company. Bear market hasn't stop our mission to become a household name, if anything the case for Yield App to be a top, trusted, blue chip platform is stronger than ever.

messages.text: The APR comes from the options premium. E.g, when you do a buy-low, you're actually selling a put options and receive that premium. The premium sort of follows the theoretical value of a formula called Black Scholes formula. But ultimately the premium price depends on market supply and demand hence the volatility

text_entities.text: The APR comes from the options premium. E.g, when you do a buy-low, you're actually selling a put options and receive that premium. The premium sort of follows the theoretical value of a formula called Black Scholes formula. But ultimately the premium price depends on market supply and demand hence the volatility

messages.text: The APR is the annualized rate of the premium. E.g. if the options premium is 0.5 percent for 7 days. Then the annualized APR sort of equals to 0.5 percent x 365/7

text_entities.text: The APR is the annualized rate of the premium. E.g. if the options premium is 0.5 percent for 7 days. Then the annualized APR sort of equals to 0.5 percent x 365/7
